import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_error

import warnings

Daily Temperature

In[3]:
tempt = pd.read_csv('../data/daily_tempt.csv')
tempt['data_ind'] = tempt['Date']
tempt = tempt.set_index('data_ind')
tempt.index = pd.to_datetime(tempt.index)
In[4]:
train_tempt = tempt.loc[tempt.index < '1988-01-01']
val_tempt = tempt.loc[tempt.index >= '1988-01-01']

y_train = train_tempt['mean-tempt']
y_val = val_tempt['mean-tempt']

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 5))
train_tempt.plot(ax=ax, label='Training Set', title='Daily Temperature test/val split', color='#3A92E4')
val_tempt.plot(ax=ax, label='Val Set', color='#3AE48C')
ax.axvline('1988-01-01', color='black', ls='--')
ax.legend(['Training Set', 'Val Set'])
plt.show()

My series has an additive seasonality amplitude is almost constant, and also series has not a clear trend.

In[5]:
seasonal_add_model = ExponentialSmoothing(
    y_train,
    trend=None,
    seasonal='add',
    seasonal_periods=365
)

seasonal_add_fit = seasonal_add_model.fit(optimized=True)
seasonal_add_forecast = seasonal_add_fit.forecast(len(y_val))

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 5))

y_train.plot(ax=ax, label='Training Set', color='#3A92E4')
y_val.plot(ax=ax, label='Val Set', color='#3AE48C')
seasonal_add_forecast.plot(ax=ax, label='Seasonal Add forecast', color='red')

ax.axvline('1988-01-01', color='black', ls='--')
ax.set_ylabel("Mean temperature")
ax.set_xlabel("Year")
ax.set_title('Daily Temperature  with additive seasonality')
ax.legend()

plt.show()

In[8]:
co2 = pd.read_csv('../data/weekly_co2.csv')
co2 = co2[['Date', 'average']]
co2['data_ind'] = co2['Date']
co2 = co2.set_index('data_ind')
co2.index = pd.to_datetime(co2.index)
In[9]:
train_co2 = co2.loc[co2.index < '2015-07-05']
val_co2 = co2.loc[co2.index >= '2015-07-05']

y_train = train_co2['average']
y_val = val_co2['average']

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 5))
train_co2.plot(ax=ax, label='Training Set', title='Weekly Co2 test/val split', color='#3A92E4')
val_co2.plot(ax=ax, label='Val Set', color='#3AE48C')
ax.axvline('2015-07-05', color='black', ls='--')
ax.legend(['Training Set', 'Val Set'])
plt.show()

My series has a clear trend, and a multiplicative seasonality we will compare seasonal_periods=52 and seasonal_periods=104 and also we will do the same for additive seasonality.

In[10]:
# Additive seasonality 52
seasonal_add_model = ExponentialSmoothing(
    y_train,
    trend='add',
    # damped_trend=True,
    seasonal='add',
    seasonal_periods=52
)

seasonal_add_fit = seasonal_add_model.fit(optimized=True)
seasonal_add_forecast_52 = seasonal_add_fit.forecast(len(y_val))

# Additive seasonality 104
seasonal_add_model = ExponentialSmoothing(
    y_train,
    trend='add',
    # damped_trend=True,
    seasonal='add',
    seasonal_periods=104
)

seasonal_add_fit = seasonal_add_model.fit(optimized=True)
seasonal_add_forecast_104 = seasonal_add_fit.forecast(len(y_val))

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 5))

y_train.plot(ax=ax, label='Training Set', color='#3A92E4')
y_val.plot(ax=ax, label='Val Set', color='#3AE48C')
seasonal_add_forecast_52.plot(ax=ax, label='Seasonal Add forecast 52', color='#6203FC', alpha=0.7)
seasonal_add_forecast_104.plot(ax=ax, label='Seasonal Add forecast 104', color='#DD03FC', alpha=0.7)

ax.axvline('2015-07-05', color='black', ls='--')
ax.set_ylabel("Average Co2")
ax.set_xlabel("Year")
ax.set_title('Weekly Co2  with additive seasonality')
ax.legend()

plt.show()

Here we are comparing Additive seasonality with seasonal_periods=51 and seasonal_periods=104.

We see that seasonal_periods=104 shows itself better.

y_val = val_aep['AEP_MW']

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 5))
train_aep.plot(ax=ax, label='Training Set', title='Hourly AEP test/val split', color='#3A92E4')

My series has an additive seasonality but multiplicative seasonality we will also try, and series has not a clear trend.

In[18]:
seasonal_add_model = ExponentialSmoothing(
    y_train,
    trend=None,
    seasonal='add',
    seasonal_periods=4464
)

seasonal_add_fit = seasonal_add_model.fit(optimized=True)
seasonal_add_forecast = seasonal_add_fit.forecast(len(y_val))

seasonal_mul_model = ExponentialSmoothing(
    y_train,
    trend=None,
    seasonal='mul',
    seasonal_periods=4464
)

seasonal_mul_fit = seasonal_mul_model.fit(optimized=True)
seasonal_mul_forecast = seasonal_mul_fit.forecast(len(y_val))

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 5))

y_train.plot(ax=ax, label='Training Set', color='#3A92E4')
y_val.plot(ax=ax, label='Val Set', color='#3AE48C')
seasonal_add_forecast.plot(ax=ax, label='Seasonal Add forecast', color='#6203FC', alpha=0.7)
seasonal_mul_forecast.plot(ax=ax, label='Seasonal Mul forecast',color='#DD03FC', alpha=0.7)

ax.axvline('2015-10-27 06:00:00', color='black', ls='--')
ax.set_ylabel("Mean temperature")
ax.set_xlabel("Year")
ax.set_title('Daily Temperature  with additive seasonality')
ax.legend()

plt.show()

Our seasonal period is 4464, hear we're comparing additive and multiplicative seasonality.

And we see that multiplicative has better result.

In[19]:
# Additive seasonality
add_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_val, seasonal_add_forecast)
add_rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_val, seasonal_add_forecast))
add_mape = np.mean(np.abs((y_val - seasonal_add_forecast) / y_val)) * 100
# Multiplicative seasonality
mul_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_val, seasonal_mul_forecast)
mul_rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_val, seasonal_mul_forecast))
mul_mape = np.mean(np.abs((y_val - seasonal_mul_forecast) / y_val)) * 100

print(f" Additive seasonality:  Multiplicative seasonality:"
      f"\n MAE  = {add_mae:.3f};       MAE  = {mul_mae:.3f};"
      f"\n RMSE = {add_rmse:.3f};       RMSE = {mul_rmse:.3f};"
      f"\n MAPE = {add_mape:.3f};         MAPE = {mul_mape:.3f}.")
